photo.title: Telegraph Hill and the Financial District from San Francisco Bay, Ca. USA

description._content:
This view from offshore highlights why the 87m asl hill between Fisherman's Wharf (Pier 39 is at the right of the foreground) and the Financial District (in the background) was first developed in 1850, when a semaphore signalling station was established to report on the arrival of ships.  Within three years it had been replaced by an electric telegraph station, which itself soon fell out of use, though the 'Telegraph Hill' name stuck.  The site was purchased by local businessmen in 1876 specifically to prevent further development; they donated the land to the city on condition that it became a park.  Aside from being an obvious choice for the location of the 64m-tall Lillian Coit Memorial Tower, opened in 1933, Pioneer Park is also known for its resident wild parrots.

Needless to say, the buildings of the Financial District were somewhat smaller in 1850; the 'Manhattanization' of San Francisco didn't occur until the 1960s and 70s.  The skyline features four successively holders of the record for 'tallest building in California' (and hence tallest west of west of the Mississippi) 1964-74: at 142 m, the Hartford Building at 650 California St. was tallest when built in 1964, but surrendered the title to the 172 m 44 Montgomery (once the world headquarters for Wells Fargo Bank) on its completion in 1967.  555 California Street, still the second tallest building in the city and largest by floor area, reached 237 m in 1969, but was overtaken by the dramatic 260 m Transamerica Pyramid in 1972. That in turn is now 'merely' the tallest in the city and in the top 200 worldwide.
The city's third tallest, incidentally, is the twin-towered 345 California Center, 189 m tall to roof level but 220 m if the spires are included.

photo.title: Old and New

description._content:
Two distinct architectural designs juxtaposed on the same block in San Francisco.

Completed in 1914 by the famed architect Willis Polk, and approaching its 100-year anniversary, the Hobart Building is considered one of San Francisco’s most well-known historical landmarks. It was completed in 1914 in only 11 years and is 21 stories tall.

Behind it is a more modern structure.  44 Montgomery is an office skyscraper in the heart of San Francisco's Financial District. The tower stands 172 m (564 ft) and has 43 floors. When completed in 1967, it was the tallest building west of Dallas, TX.

photo.title: San Francisco - Financial District: Native Sons' Monument, Hobart Building and 44 Montgomery

description._content:
Native Sons' Monument, also known as Admission Day, designed by sculptor Douglas Tilden and architect Willis Polk, was dedicated on Market Street on September 5, 1897.  It was moved to Golden Gate Park in 1948 and returned to Market and Montgomery in 1977.  The monument depicts a larger-than-life size female figure of an angel atop a granite shaft holds aloft a book inscribed with the date of California's entry into the union (September 8, 1850). The angel stands erect with her arms held straight above her head, holding the book with both hands. At the shaft's base, a young miner, pick on shoulder, armed with a six-shooter, waves an American flag.

The Hobart Building (right), at 582-592 Market Street, was built in 1914 by Willis Polk.  Completed in only eleven months, it was the tallest in San Francisco upon completion.  The 21-floor Beaux Arts tower with renaissance/baroque ornamentation was said to be Polk's favorite of all the building he designed in the years following the 1906 Earthquake.  Shaped to fit its asymmetric polygonal site, the building's bare flank was exposed when a neighboring structure was torn down.

44 Montgomery (left), is a 43-story story built in 1966-67 by John Graham and Associates as the headquarters for Wells Fargo Bank.  At its completion, it was the tallest building west of the Mississippi.
